div.p:
Aene. 1.Taken from an other place in VIRGIL, where EOLVS at the com|mand of IVNO, lets forth the winde;
Aene. 1. —ac venti velut agmine facto
Quâ data porta ruunt, & terras turbine perflant.

This, and the whole frame, was couered with a curtaine of silke, pain|ted like a thicke cloud, and at the approach of the K. was instantly to be drawne. The Allegorie being, that those clouds were gathered vpon the face of the Citie, through their long want of his most wished sight: but now, as at the rising of the Sunne, all mists were dispersed and fled. When sodainely, vpon silence made to the Musickes, a voyce was heard to vtter this verse;



                           Claud. de laud. Stil. lib. 3.
                           Totus adest oculis, aderat qui mentibus olim,
